# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: radius-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] Authentication is concerned with proving identity, authorization with granting permissions, accounting with maintaining a continuous and robust audit trail via logging.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] Common network protocols providing this functionality include TACACS+, RADIUS, and Diameter.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] In some related but distinct contexts, the term AAA has been used to refer to protocol-specific information.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] For example, Diameter uses the URI scheme AAA, which also stands for "Authentication, Authorization and Accounting", as well as the Diameter-based Protocol AAAS, which stands for "Authentication, Authorization and Accounting with Secure Transport".
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] These protocols were defined by the Internet Engineering Task Force in RFC 6733 and are intended to provide an AAA framework for applications, such as network access or IP mobility in both local and roaming situations.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] However, the AAA paradigm is used more widely in the computer security industry.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] AAA servers in CDMA data networks are entities that provide Internet Protocol (IP) functionality to support the functions of authentication, authorization and accounting.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] The AAA server in the CDMA wireless data network architecture is similar to the HLR in the CDMA wireless voice network architecture.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] Current AAA servers communicate using the RADIUS protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] As such, TIA specifications refer to AAA servers as RADIUS servers.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] While at one point it was expected that Diameter was to replace RADIUS, that has not happened.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] Diameter is largely used only in the mobile (3G/4G/5G) space, and RADIUS is used everywhere else.
[src:radius-protocol/aaa-computer-security] The behavior of AAA servers (radius servers) in the CDMA2000 wireless IP network is specified in TIA-835.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The name is a play on words, derived from the RADIUS protocol, which is the predecessor (a diameter is twice the radius).
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Diameter is not directly backward compatible but provides an upgrade path for RADIUS.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Also: Like RADIUS, it is intended to work in both local and roaming AAA situations.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] It uses TCP or SCTP, unlike RADIUS which uses UDP.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Unlike RADIUS it includes no encryption but can be protected by transport-level security (IPSEC or TLS).
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The base size of the AV identifier is 32 bit unlike RADIUS which uses 8 bit as the base AV identifier size.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Like RADIUS, it supports stateless as well as stateful modes.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Like RADIUS, it supports application-layer acknowledgment and defines failover.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Diameter is used for many different interfaces defined by the 3GPP standards, with each interface typically defining new commands and attributes.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] A *Diameter Application* is not a software application but is a protocol based on the Diameter base protocol defined in RFC 6733 (obsoletes RFC 3588) and RFC 7075.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Each application is defined by an application identifier and can add new command codes and/or new mandatory AVPs (Attribute-Value Pair).
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Adding a new optional AVP does not require a new application.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] communicate using the Diameter protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol was initially developed by Pat R.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Calhoun, Glen Zorn, and Ping Pan in 1998 to provide a framework for authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) that could overcome the limitations of RADIUS.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] At the time Diameter was designed, RADIUS was believed to have issues with reliability, scalability, security, and flexibility.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] RADIUS also did not support large policies which were needed for telephony applications.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol defines a policy protocol used by clients to perform Policy, AAA, and resource control.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] This allows a single server to handle policies for many services.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Like RADIUS, Diameter provides AAA functionality, but uses TCP and SCTP instead of UDP, therefore delegating detection and handling of communication problems to those protocols.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol is enhanced further by the development of the 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS).
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The S6a, S6b, Gx, Gy, Sy, Rx, Cx, Dh, Dx, Rf, Ro, Sh and Zh interfaces are supported by Diameter applications.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Through the use of extensions, the protocol was designed to be extensible to support proxies, brokers, strong security, mobile IP, network-access servers (NASREQ), accounting and resource management.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Diameter base protocol is defined by RFC 6733 (Obsoletes: RFC 3588 and RFC 5719) and defines the minimum requirements for an AAA protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] *Diameter Applications* can extend the base protocol by adding new commands, attributes, or both.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Diameter security is provided by IPsec or TLS.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The IANA has assigned TCP and SCTP port number 3868 to Diameter, as stated in section 11.4 of RFC 6733.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The packet consists of a Diameter header and a variable number of Attribute–Value Pairs, or AVPs, for encapsulating information relevant to the Diameter message.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] This field indicates the version of the Diameter Base Protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] As of 2014, the only value supported is 1.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Message Length field indicates the length of the Diameter message in bytes, including the header fields and the padded AVPs.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**R**" (Request) bit – If set, the message is a request.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**P**" (Proxiable) bit – If set, the message MAY be proxied, relayed or redirected.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] If cleared, the message MUST be locally processed.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**E**" (Error) bit – If set, the message contains a protocol error, and the message will not conform to the CCF described for this command.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Messages with the "E" bit set are commonly referred to as error messages.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] This bit MUST NOT be set in request messages.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**T**" (Potentially re-transmitted message) bit – This flag is set after a link failover procedure, to aid the removal of duplicate requests.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] It is set when resending requests not yet acknowledged as an indication of a possible duplicate due to a link failure.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Each command Request/Answer pair is assigned a command code.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Whether it is the request or answer is identified via the 'R' bit in the Command Flags field of the header.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The values 0-255 are reserved for RADIUS backward compatibility.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The values 256-16777213 are for permanent, standard commands allocated by IANA.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The values 16777214 and 16777215 (hex 0xFFFFFE and 0xFFFFFF) are reserved for experimental and testing purposes.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] A Command Code is used to determine the action that is to be taken for a particular message.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Application-ID is used to identify for which Diameter application the message is applicable.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The application can be an authentication application, an accounting application, or a vendor-specific application.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Diameter agents conforming to a certain Diameter extension publicize its support by including a specific value of in the Auth-Application-ID Attribute of the Capabilities-Exchange-Request (CER) and Capabilities-Exchange-Answer (CEA) command.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The value of the Application-ID field in the header is the same as any relevant Application-ID AVPs contained in the message.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] For instance, the value of the Application-ID and of the Auth-Application-ID Attribute in the Credit-Control-Request (CCR) and Credit-Control-Answer (CCA) Command for the Diameter Credit-Control Application is 4.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Hop-by-Hop Identifier is an unsigned 32-bit integer field (in network byte order) that is used to match the requests with their answers as the same value in the request is used in the response.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol requires that relaying and proxying agents maintain transaction state, which is used for failover purposes.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Transaction state implies that upon forwarding a request, its Hop-by-Hop Identifier is saved; the field is replaced with a locally unique identifier, which is restored to its original value when the corresponding answer is received.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The request's state is released upon receipt of the answer.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Received answers that do not match a known Hop-by-Hop Identifier are ignored by the Diameter agent.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] In case of redirecting agents, the Hop-by-Hop Identifier is maintained in the header as the Diameter agent responds with an answer message.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The End-to-End Identifier is an unsigned 32-bit integer field (in network byte order) that is used to detect duplicate messages along with the combination of the Origin-Host AVP.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] When creating a request, the End-to-End Identifier is set to a locally unique value.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The End-to-End Identifier is not modified by Diameter agents of any kind, and the same value in the corresponding request is used in the answer.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] For simplicity, AVP Flag "**V**" bit Means **Vendor Specific**; "**M**" bit means **Mandatory**; "**P**" bit means **Protected**.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**V**" bit, known as the Vendor-Specific bit, indicates whether the optional **Vendor-ID** field is present in the AVP header.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] When set the AVP Code belongs to the specific vendor code address space.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**M**" bit, known as the Mandatory bit, indicates whether support of the AVP is required.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] If an AVP with the "**M**" bit set is received by a Diameter client, server, proxy, or translation agent and either the AVP or its value is unrecognized, the message *must* be rejected.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Diameter Relay and redirect agents *must not* reject messages with unrecognized AVPs.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The "**P**" bit indicates the need for encryption for end-to-end security.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The RFC 3588 defines a core state machine for maintaining connections between peers and processing messages.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] This is part of the basic protocol functionality and all stacks should support it and as such abstract from the connectivity related operations.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Additionally, application specific state machines can be introduced either later or at a higher abstraction layer.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The RFC 3588 defines an authorization and an accounting state machine.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The communication between two diameter peers starts with the establishment of a transport connection (TCP or SCTP).
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The initiator then sends a Capabilities-Exchange-Request (CER) to the other peer, which responds with a Capabilities-Exchange-Answer (CEA).
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] For RFC3588 compliant peers TLS (Transport Layer Security) may optionally be negotiated.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] For RFC6733 compliant peers TLS negotiation may optionally happen before the CER/CEA.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The connection is then ready for exchanging application messages.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] If no messages have been exchanged for some time either side may send a Device-Watchdog-Request (DWR) and the other peer must respond with Device-Watchdog-Answer.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] Either side may terminate the communication by sending a Disconnect-Peer-Request (DPR) which the other peer must respond to with Disconnect-Peer-Answer.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] After that the transport connection can be disconnected.
[src:radius-protocol/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol is currently defined in the following IETF RFCs: Obsolete RFCs are indicated with strikethrough text.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, in IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi) the WPA and WPA2 standards have adopted IEEE 802.1X (with various EAP types) as the canonical authentication mechanism.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is an authentication framework, not a specific authentication mechanism.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides some common functions and negotiation of authentication methods called EAP methods.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are currently about 40 different methods defined.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Methods defined in IETF RFCs include EAP-MD5, EAP-POTP, EAP-GTC, EAP-TLS, EAP-IKEv2, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, and EAP-AKA'.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Additionally, a number of vendor-specific methods and new proposals exist.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Commonly used modern methods capable of operating in wireless networks include EAP-TLS, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, LEAP and EAP-TTLS.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Requirements for EAP methods used in wireless LAN authentication are described in RFC 4017.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The list of type and packets codes used in EAP is available from the IANA EAP Registry.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The standard also describes the conditions under which the AAA key management requirements described in RFC 4962 can be satisfied.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol (LEAP) method was developed by Cisco Systems prior to the IEEE ratification of the 802.11i security standard.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco distributed the protocol through the CCX (Cisco Certified Extensions) as part of getting 802.1X and dynamic WEP adoption into the industry in the absence of a standard.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] There is no native support for LEAP in any Windows operating system, but it is widely supported by third-party client software most commonly included with WLAN (wireless LAN) devices.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP support for Microsoft Windows 7 and Microsoft Windows Vista can be added by downloading a client add in from Cisco that provides support for both LEAP and EAP-FAST.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Due to the wide adoption of LEAP in the networking industry many other WLAN vendors claim support for LEAP.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP uses a modified version of MS-CHAP, an authentication protocol in which user credentials are not strongly protected and easily compromised; an exploit tool called ASLEAP was released in early 2004 by Joshua Wright.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco recommends that customers who absolutely must use LEAP do so only with sufficiently complex passwords, though complex passwords are difficult to administer and enforce.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco's current recommendation is to use newer and stronger EAP protocols such as EAP-FAST, PEAP, or EAP-TLS.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Transport Layer Security (EAP-TLS), defined in RFC 5216, is an IETF open standard that uses the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol, and is well-supported among wireless vendors.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is the original, standard wireless LAN EAP authentication protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is still considered one of the most secure EAP standards available, although TLS provides strong security only as long as the user understands potential warnings about false credentials, and is universally supported by all manufacturers of wireless LAN hardware and software.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Until April 2005, EAP-TLS was the only EAP type vendors needed to certify for a WPA or WPA2 logo.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are client and server implementations of EAP-TLS in 3Com, Apple, Avaya, Brocade Communications, Cisco, Enterasys Networks, Fortinet, Foundry, Hirschmann, HP, Juniper, Microsoft, and open source operating systems.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is natively supported in Mac OS X 10.3 and above, wpa_supplicant, Windows 2000 SP4, Windows XP and above, Windows Mobile 2003 and above, Windows CE 4.2, and Apple's iOS mobile operating system.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Unlike most TLS implementations of HTTPS, such as on the World Wide Web, the majority of implementations of EAP-TLS require mutual authentication using client-side X.509 certificates without giving the option to disable the requirement, even though the standard does not mandate their use.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Some have identified this as having the potential to dramatically reduce adoption of EAP-TLS and prevent "open" but encrypted access points.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] This would allow for situations much like HTTPS, where a wireless hotspot allows free access and does not authenticate station clients but station clients wish to use encryption (IEEE 802.11i-2004 i.e.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] WPA2) and potentially authenticate the wireless hotspot.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] There have also been proposals to use IEEE 802.11u for access points to signal that they allow EAP-TLS using only server-side authentication, using the standard EAP-TLS IETF type instead of a vendor-specific EAP type.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The requirement for a client-side certificate, however unpopular it may be, is what gives EAP-TLS its authentication strength and illustrates the classic convenience vs. security trade-off.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] With a client-side certificate, a compromised password is not enough to break into EAP-TLS enabled systems because the intruder still needs to have the client-side certificate; indeed, a password is not even needed, as it is only used to encrypt the client-side certificate for storage.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The highest security available is when the "private keys" of client-side certificate are housed in smart cards.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is because there is no way to steal a client-side certificate's corresponding private key from a smart card without stealing the card itself.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is more likely that the physical theft of a smart card would be noticed (and the smart card immediately revoked) than a (typical) password theft would be noticed.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition, the private key on a smart card is typically encrypted using a PIN that only the owner of the smart card knows, minimizing its utility for a thief even before the card has been reported stolen and revoked.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 was the only IETF Standards Track based EAP method when it was first defined in the original RFC for EAP, RFC 2284.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It offers minimal security; the MD5 hash function is vulnerable to dictionary attacks, and does not support key generation, which makes it unsuitable for use with dynamic WEP, or WPA/WPA2 enterprise.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 differs from other EAP methods in that it only provides authentication of the EAP peer to the EAP server but not mutual authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] By not providing EAP server authentication, this EAP method is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 support was first included in Windows 2000 and deprecated in Windows Vista.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Protected One-Time Password (EAP-POTP), which is described in RFC 4793, is an EAP method developed by RSA Laboratories that uses one-time password (OTP) tokens, such as a handheld hardware device or a hardware or software module running on a personal computer, to generate authentication keys.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-POTP can be used to provide unilateral or mutual authentication and key material in protocols that use EAP.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-POTP method provides two-factor user authentication, meaning that a user needs both physical access to a token and knowledge of a personal identification number (PIN) to perform authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Pre-shared key (EAP-PSK), defined in RFC 4764, is an EAP method for mutual authentication and session key derivation using a pre-shared key (PSK).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides a protected communication channel, when mutual authentication is successful, for both parties to communicate and is designed for authentication over insecure networks such as IEEE 802.11.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PSK is documented in an experimental RFC that provides a lightweight and extensible EAP method that does not require any public-key cryptography.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP method protocol exchange is done in a minimum of four messages.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Password (EAP-PWD), defined in RFC 5931, is an EAP method which uses a shared password for authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The password may be a low-entropy one and may be drawn from some set of possible passwords, like a dictionary, which is available to an attacker.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The underlying key exchange is resistant to active attack, passive attack, and dictionary attack.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PWD is in the base of Android 4.0 (ICS).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is in FreeRADIUS and Radiator RADIUS servers, and it is in hostapd and wpa_supplicant.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Tunneled Transport Layer Security (EAP-TTLS) is an EAP protocol that extends TLS.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It was co-developed by Funk Software and Certicom and is widely supported across platforms.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft did not incorporate native support for the EAP-TTLS protocol in Windows XP, Vista, or 7.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Supporting TTLS on these platforms requires third-party Encryption Control Protocol (ECP) certified software.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft Windows started EAP-TTLS support with Windows 8, support for EAP-TTLS appeared in Windows Phone version 8.1.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The client can, but does not have to be authenticated via a CA-signed PKI certificate to the server.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] This greatly simplifies the setup procedure since a certificate is not needed on every client.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] After the server is securely authenticated to the client via its CA certificate and optionally the client to the server, the server can then use the established secure connection ("tunnel") to authenticate the client.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It can use an existing and widely deployed authentication protocol and infrastructure, incorporating legacy password mechanisms and authentication databases, while the secure tunnel provides protection from eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Note that the user's name is never transmitted in unencrypted clear text, improving privacy.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Two distinct versions of EAP-TTLS exist: original EAP-TTLS (a.k.a.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TTLSv0 is described in RFC 5281, EAP-TTLSv1 is available as an Internet draft.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] 2 (EAP-IKEv2) is an EAP method based on the Internet Key Exchange protocol version 2 (IKEv2).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides mutual authentication and session key establishment between an EAP peer and an EAP server.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] High-entropy bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is possible to use a different authentication credential (and thereby technique) in each direction.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, the EAP server authenticates itself using public/private key pair and the EAP peer using symmetric key.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] However, not all of the nine theoretical combinations are expected in practice.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Specifically, the standard RFC 5106 lists four use cases: The server authenticating with an asymmetric key pair while the client uses any of the three methods; and that both sides use a symmetric key.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-IKEv2 is described in RFC 5106, and a prototype implementation exists.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Flexible Authentication via Secure Tunneling (EAP-FAST; RFC 4851) is a protocol proposal by Cisco Systems as a replacement for LEAP.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol was designed to address the weaknesses of LEAP while preserving the "lightweight" implementation.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of server certificates is optional in EAP-FAST.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST uses a Protected Access Credential (PAC) to establish a TLS tunnel in which client credentials are verified.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] When automatic PAC provisioning is enabled, EAP-FAST has a vulnerability where an attacker can intercept the PAC and use that to compromise user credentials.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] This vulnerability is mitigated by manual PAC provisioning or by using server certificates for the PAC provisioning phase.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is worth noting that the PAC file is issued on a per-user basis.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is a requirement in RFC 4851 sec 7.4.4 so if a new user logs on the network from a device, a new PAC file must be provisioned first.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is one reason why it is difficult not to run EAP-FAST in insecure anonymous provisioning mode.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The alternative is to use device passwords instead, but then the device is validated on the network not the user.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST can be used without PAC files, falling back to normal TLS.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST is natively supported in Apple OS X 10.4.8 and newer.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco supplies an EAP-FAST module for Windows Vista and later operating systems which have an extensible EAPHost architecture for new authentication methods and supplicants.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Tunnel Extensible Authentication Protocol (TEAP; RFC 7170) is a tunnel-based EAP method that enables secure communication between a peer and a server by using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol to establish a mutually authenticated tunnel.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Within the tunnel, TLV (Type-Length-Value) objects are used to convey authentication-related data between the EAP peer and the EAP server.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition to peer authentication, TEAP allows the peer to ask the server for a certificate by sending a request in PKCS#10 format.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] After receiving the certificate request and authenticating the peer, the server can provision a certificate to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The server can also distribute trusted root certificates to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both operations are enclosed into the corresponding TLVs and happen securely within the already established TLS tunnel.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Subscriber Identity Module (EAP-SIM) is used for authentication and session key distribution using the subscriber identity module (SIM) from the Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] GSM cellular networks use a subscriber identity module card to carry out user authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-SIM uses a SIM authentication algorithm between the client and an Authentication, Authorization and Accounting (AAA) server providing mutual authentication between the client and the network.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] In EAP-SIM the communication between the SIM card and the Authentication Centre (AuC) replaces the need for a pre-established password between the client and the AAA server.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The A3/A8 algorithms are being run a few times, with different 128 bit challenges, so there will be more 64 bit Kc-s which will be combined/mixed to create stronger keys (Kc-s won't be used directly).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The lack of mutual authentication in GSM has also been overcome.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Extensible Authentication Protocol Method for Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS) Authentication and Key Agreement (EAP-AKA), is an EAP mechanism for authentication and session key distribution using the UMTS Subscriber Identity Module (USIM).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-AKA' variant of EAP-AKA, defined in RFC 5448, and is used for non-3GPP access to a 3GPP core network.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Generic Token Card, or EAP-GTC, is an EAP method created by Cisco as an alternative to PEAPv0/EAP-MSCHAPv2 and defined in RFC 2284 and RFC 3748.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-GTC carries a text challenge from the authentication server, and a reply generated by a security token.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The PEAP-GTC authentication mechanism allows generic authentication to a number of databases such as Novell Directory Service (NDS) and Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP), as well as the use of a one-time password.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP with the encrypted key exchange, or EAP-EKE, is one of the few EAP methods that provide secure mutual authentication using short passwords and no need for public key certificates.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is a three-round exchange, based on the Diffie-Hellman variant of the well-known EKE protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Nimble out-of-band authentication for EAP (EAP-NOOB) is a generic bootstrapping solution for devices which have no pre-configured authentication credentials and which are not yet registered on any server.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is especially useful for Internet-of-Things (IoT) gadgets and toys that come with no information about any owner, network or server.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Authentication for this EAP method is based on a user-assisted out-of-band (OOB) channel between the server and peer.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB supports many types of OOB channels such as QR codes, NFC tags, audio etc. and unlike other EAP methods, the protocol security has been verified by formal modeling of the specification with ProVerif and MCRL2 tools.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB performs an Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) over the in-band EAP channel.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The user then confirms this exchange by transferring the OOB message.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Users can transfer the OOB message from the peer to the server, when for example, the device is a smart TV that can show a QR code.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Alternatively, users can transfer the OOB message from the server to the peer, when for example, the device being bootstrapped is a camera that can only read a QR code.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is not a wire protocol; instead it only defines message formats.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Each protocol that uses EAP defines a way to encapsulate EAP messages within that protocol's messages.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The encapsulation of EAP over IEEE 802 is defined in IEEE 802.1X and known as "EAP over LANs" or EAPOL.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAPOL was originally designed for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet in 802.1X-2001, but was clarified to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless and Fiber Distributed Data Interface (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12, adopted as ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2004.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAPOL protocol was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) and IEEE 802.1AR (Initial Device Identity, IDevID) in 802.1X-2010.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protected Extensible Authentication Protocol, also known as Protected EAP or simply PEAP, is a protocol that encapsulates EAP within a potentially encrypted and authenticated Transport Layer Security (TLS) tunnel.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The purpose was to correct deficiencies in EAP; EAP assumed a protected communication channel, such as that provided by physical security, so facilities for protection of the EAP conversation were not provided.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAP was jointly developed by Cisco Systems, Microsoft, and RSA Security.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv0 was the version included with Microsoft Windows XP and was nominally defined in draft-kamath-pppext-peapv0-00.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 and PEAPv2 were defined in different versions of *draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap*.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 was defined in draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-00 through draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-05, and PEAPv2 was defined in versions beginning with draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-06.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol only specifies chaining multiple EAP mechanisms and not any specific method.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of the EAP-MSCHAPv2 and EAP-GTC methods are the most commonly supported.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both the RADIUS and Diameter AAA protocols can encapsulate EAP messages.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] They are often used by Network Access Server (NAS) devices to forward EAP packets between IEEE 802.1X endpoints and AAA servers to facilitate IEEE 802.1X.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA) is an IP-based protocol that allows a device to authenticate itself with a network to be granted access.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA will not define any new authentication protocol, key distribution, key agreement or key derivation protocols; for these purposes, EAP will be used, and PANA will carry the EAP payload.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA allows dynamic service provider selection, supports various authentication methods, is suitable for roaming users, and is independent from the link layer mechanisms.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP was originally an authentication extension for the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP).
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] PPP has supported EAP since EAP was created as an alternative to the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) and the Password Authentication Protocol (PAP), which were eventually incorporated into EAP.
[src:radius-protocol/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP extension to PPP was first defined in RFC 2284, now obsoleted by RFC 3748.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The standard directly addresses an attack technique called Hardware Addition where an attacker posing as a guest, customer or staff smuggles a hacking device into the building that they then plug into the network giving them full access.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] A notable example of the issue occurred in 2005 when a machine attached to Walmart's network hacked thousands of their servers.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] IEEE 802.1X defines the encapsulation of the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) over wired IEEE 802 networks and over 802.11 wireless networks, which is known as "EAP over LAN" or EAPOL.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL was originally specified for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet, IEEE 802.5 Token Ring, and FDDI (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12 and ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2001, but was extended to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless in 802.1X-2004.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The EAPOL was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE ("MACsec") and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity, DevID) in 802.1X-2010 to support service identification and optional point to point encryption over the internal LAN segment.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X is part of the logical link control (LLC) sublayer of the 802 reference model.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X authentication involves three parties: a supplicant, an authenticator, and an authentication server.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The **supplicant** is a client device (such as a laptop) that wishes to attach to the LAN/WLAN.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The term 'supplicant' is also used interchangeably to refer to the software running on the client that provides credentials to the authenticator.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Authentication servers typically run software supporting the RADIUS and EAP protocols.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] In some cases, the authentication server software may be running on the authenticator hardware.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator acts like a security guard to a protected network.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant (i.e., client device) is not allowed access through the authenticator to the protected side of the network until the supplicant's identity has been validated and authorized.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] With 802.1X port-based authentication, the supplicant must initially provide the required credentials to the authenticator - these will have been specified in advance by the network administrator and could include a user name/password or a permitted digital certificate.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator forwards these credentials to the authentication server to decide whether access is to be granted.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] If the authentication server determines the credentials are valid, it informs the authenticator, which in turn allows the supplicant (client device) to access resources located on the protected side of the network.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL operates over the data link layer, and in Ethernet II framing protocol has an EtherType value of 0x888E.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2001 defines two logical port entities for an authenticated port—the "controlled port" and the "uncontrolled port".
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The controlled port is manipulated by the 802.1X PAE (Port Access Entity) to allow (in the authorized state) or prevent (in the unauthorized state) network traffic ingress and egress to/from the controlled port.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The uncontrolled port is used by the 802.1X PAE to transmit and receive EAPOL frames.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2004 defines the equivalent port entities for the supplicant; so a supplicant implementing 802.1X-2004 may prevent higher-level protocols from being used if it is not content that authentication has successfully completed.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] This is particularly useful when an EAP method providing mutual authentication is used, as the supplicant can prevent data leakage when connected to an unauthorized network.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] **Initiation** To initiate authentication the authenticator will periodically transmit EAP-Request Identity frames to a special Layer 2 MAC address (*01:80:C2:00:00:03*) on the local network segment.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant listens at this address, and on receipt of the EAP-Request Identity frame, it responds with an EAP-Response Identity frame containing an identifier for the supplicant such as a User ID.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator then encapsulates this Identity response in a RADIUS Access-Request packet and forwards it on to the authentication server.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant may also initiate or restart authentication by sending an EAPOL-Start frame to the authenticator, which will then reply with an EAP-Request Identity frame.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] **Negotiation** *(Technically EAP negotiation)* The authentication server sends a reply (encapsulated in a RADIUS Access-Challenge packet) to the authenticator, containing an EAP Request specifying the EAP Method (The type of EAP based authentication it wishes the supplicant to perform).
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator encapsulates the EAP Request in an EAPOL frame and transmits it to the supplicant.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] At this point, the supplicant can start using the requested EAP Method, or do a NAK ("Negative Acknowledgement") and respond with the EAP Methods it is willing to perform.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] If authentication is successful, the authenticator sets the port to the "authorized" state and normal traffic is allowed.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] If it is unsuccessful, the port remains in the "unauthorized" state.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] When the supplicant logs off, it sends an EAPOL-logoff message to the authenticator, the authenticator then sets the port to the "unauthorized" state, once again blocking all non-EAP traffic.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] An open-source project named Open1X produces a client, Xsupplicant.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] This client is currently available for both Linux and Windows.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The main drawbacks of the Open1X client are that it does not provide comprehensible and extensive user documentation and that most Linux vendors do not provide a package for it.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The more general wpa_supplicant can be used for 802.11 wireless networks and wired networks.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Both support a very wide range of EAP types.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] ChromeOS has supported 802.1X since mid-2011.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Avenda Systems provides a supplicant for Windows, Linux and macOS.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] They also have a plugin for the Microsoft NAP framework.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Avenda also offers health checking agents.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Windows defaults to not responding to 802.1X authentication requests for 20 minutes after a failed authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] This can cause significant disruption to clients.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The block period can be configured using the HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\dot3svc\BlockTime DWORD value (HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\wlansvc\BlockTime for wireless networks) in the registry (entered in minutes).
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] A hotfix is required for Windows XP SP3 and Windows Vista SP2 to make the period configurable.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Wildcard server certificates are not supported by EAPHost, the Windows component that provides EAP support in the operating system.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The implication of this is that when using a commercial certification authority, individual certificates must be purchased.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Windows XP has major issues with its handling of IP address changes resulting from user-based 802.1X authentication that changes the VLAN and thus subnet of clients.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Microsoft has stated that it will not backport the SSO feature from Vista that resolves these issues.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] If users are not logging in with roaming profiles, a hotfix must be downloaded and installed if authenticating via PEAP with PEAP-MSCHAPv2.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Windows Vista-based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, as a result, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, consequently, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 does not respond to 802.1X authentication requests after initial 802.1X authentication fails.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Windows PE does not have native support for 802.1X.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] However, support can be added to WinPE 2.1 and WinPE 3.0 through hotfixes that are available from Microsoft.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Although full documentation is not yet available, preliminary documentation for the use of these hotfixes is available via a Microsoft blog.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Most Linux distributions support 802.1X via wpa_supplicant and desktop integration like NetworkManager.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The iPhone and iPod Touch support 802.1X since the release of iOS 2.0. macOS has offered native support since Mac OS X Panther.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] As of iOS 17 and macOS 14, Apple devices support connecting to 802.1X networks using EAP-TLS with TLS 1.3 (EAP-TLS 1.3).
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Additionally, devices running iOS/iPadOS/tvOS 17 or later support wired 802.1X networks.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Android has support for 802.1X since the release of 1.6 Donut.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] eduroam (the international roaming service), mandates the use of 802.1X authentication when providing network access to guests visiting from other eduroam-enabled institutions.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] BT (British Telecom, PLC) employs Identity Federation for authentication in services delivered to a wide variety of industries and governments.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Not all devices support 802.1X authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Examples include network printers, Ethernet-based electronics like environmental sensors, cameras, and wireless phones.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] For those devices to be used in a protected network environment, alternative mechanisms must be provided to authenticate them.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] One option would be to disable 802.1X on that port, but that leaves that port unprotected and open for abuse.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Another slightly more reliable option is to use the MAB option.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] When MAB is configured on a port, that port will first try to check if the connected device is 802.1X compliant, and if no reaction is received from the connected device, it will try to authenticate with the AAA server using the connected device's MAC address as username and password.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The network administrator then must make provisions on the RADIUS server to authenticate those MAC addresses, either by adding them as regular users or implementing additional logic to resolve them in a network inventory database.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Many managed Ethernet switches offer options for this.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] In the summer of 2005, Microsoft's Steve Riley posted an article (based on the original research of Microsoft MVP Svyatoslav Pidgorny) detailing a serious vulnerability in the 802.1X protocol, involving a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] Riley suggests that for wired networks the use of IPsec or a combination of IPsec and 802.1X would be more secure.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL-Logoff frames transmitted by the 802.1X supplicant are sent in the clear and contain no data derived from the credential exchange that initially authenticated the client.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] They are therefore trivially easy to spoof on shared media and can be used as part of a targeted DoS on both wired and wireless LANs.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] In an EAPOL-Logoff attack, a malicious third party with access to the medium the authenticator is attached to repeatedly sends forged EAPOL-Logoff frames from the target device's MAC Address.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator (believing that the targeted device wishes to end its authentication session) closes the target's authentication session, blocking traffic ingressing from the target, denying it access to the network.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The 802.1X-2010 specification, which began as 802.1af, addresses vulnerabilities in previous 802.1X specifications, by using MACsec IEEE 802.1AE to encrypt data between logical ports (running on top of a physical port) and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity / DevID) authenticated devices.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] As a stopgap, until these enhancements are widely implemented, some vendors have extended the 802.1X-2001 and 802.1X-2004 protocol, allowing multiple concurrent authentication sessions to occur on a single port.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] While this prevents traffic from devices with unauthenticated MAC addresses ingressing on an 802.1X authenticated port, it will not stop a malicious device snooping on traffic from an authenticated device and provides no protection against MAC spoofing, or EAPOL-Logoff attacks.
[src:radius-protocol/ieee-802-1x] The IETF-backed alternative is the Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA), which also carries EAP, although it works at layer 3, using UDP, thus not being tied to the 802 infrastructure.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS is a client/server protocol that runs in the application layer, and can use either TCP or UDP.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Network access servers, which control access to a network, usually contain a RADIUS client component that communicates with the RADIUS server.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS is often the back-end of choice for 802.1X authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] A RADIUS server is usually a background process running on UNIX or Microsoft Windows.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The Blast-RADIUS attack breaks RADIUS when it is run on an unencrypted transport protocol like UDP.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS is an AAA (authentication, authorization, and accounting) protocol that manages network access.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS uses two types of packets to manage the full AAA process: Access-Request, which manages authentication and authorization; and Accounting-Request, which manages accounting.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Authentication and authorization are defined in RFC 2865 while accounting is described by RFC 2866.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The user or machine sends a request to a Network Access Server (NAS) to gain access to a particular network resource using access credentials.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The credentials are passed to the NAS device via the link-layer protocol—for example, Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) in the case of many dialup or DSL providers or posted in an HTTPS secure web form.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] In turn, the NAS sends a RADIUS *Access Request* message to the RADIUS server, requesting authorization to grant access via the RADIUS protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] This request includes access credentials, typically in the form of username and password or security certificate provided by the user.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Additionally, the request may contain other information which the NAS knows about the user, such as its network address or phone number, and information regarding the user's physical point of attachment to the NAS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RADIUS server checks that the information is correct using authentication schemes such as PAP, CHAP or EAP.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The user's proof of identification is verified, along with, optionally, other information related to the request, such as the user's network address or phone number, account status, and specific network service access privileges.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Historically, RADIUS servers checked the user's information against a locally stored flat file database.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Modern RADIUS servers can do this, or can refer to external sources—commonly SQL, Kerberos, LDAP, or Active Directory servers—to verify the user's credentials.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RADIUS server then returns one of three responses to the NAS: 1) Access Reject, 2) Access Challenge, or 3) Access Accept.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The user is unconditionally denied access to all requested network resources.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Reasons may include failure to provide proof of identification or an unknown or inactive user account.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Requests additional information from the user such as a secondary password, PIN, token, or card.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Access Challenge is also used in more complex authentication dialogs where a secure tunnel is established between the user machine and the Radius Server in a way that the access credentials are hidden from the NAS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Once the user is authenticated, the RADIUS server will often check that the user is authorized to use the network service requested.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] A given user may be allowed to use a company's wireless network, but not its VPN service, for example.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Again, this information may be stored locally on the RADIUS server, or may be looked up in an external source such as LDAP or Active Directory.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Each of these three RADIUS responses may include a Reply-Message attribute which may give a reason for the rejection, the prompt for the challenge, or a welcome message for the accept.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The text in the attribute can be passed on to the user in a return web page.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Authorization attributes are conveyed to the NAS stipulating terms of access to be granted.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] When a client is configured to use RADIUS, any user of the client presents authentication information to the client.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] This might be with a customizable login prompt, where the user is expected to enter their username and password.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Alternatively, the user might use a link framing protocol such as the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP), which has authentication packets which carry this information.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Once the client has obtained such information, it may choose to authenticate using RADIUS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] To do so, the client creates an "Access- Request" containing such Attributes as the user's name, the user's password, the ID of the client and the port ID which the user is accessing.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] When a password is present, it is hidden using a method based on the RSA Message Digest Algorithm MD5.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] When network access is granted to the user by the NAS, an *Accounting Start* (a RADIUS Accounting Request packet containing an Acct-Status-Type attribute with the value "start") is sent by the NAS to the RADIUS server to signal the start of the user's network access.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] "Start" records typically contain the user's identification, network address, point of attachment and a unique session identifier.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Periodically, *Interim Update* records (a RADIUS Accounting Request packet containing an Acct-Status-Type attribute with the value "interim-update") may be sent by the NAS to the RADIUS server, to update it on the status of an active session.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] "Interim" records typically convey the current session duration and information on current data usage.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Typically, the client sends Accounting-Request packets until it receives an Accounting-Response acknowledgement, using some retry interval.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The primary purpose of this data is that the user can be billed accordingly; the data is also commonly used for statistical purposes and for general network monitoring.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS facilitates this by the use of *realms*, which identify where the RADIUS server should forward the AAA requests for processing.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] A realm is commonly appended to a user's user name and delimited with an '@' sign, resembling an email address domain name.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] This is known as *postfix* notation for the realm.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Another common usage is *prefix* notation, which involves prepending the realm to the username and using '\' as a delimiter.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Modern RADIUS servers allow any character to be used as a realm delimiter, although in practice '@' and '\' are usually used.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Realms can also be compounded using both prefix and postfix notation, to allow for complicated roaming scenarios; for example, somedomain.com\username@anotherdomain.com could be a valid username with two realms.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Although realms often resemble domains, realms are arbitrary text and need not contain real domain names.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Realm formats are standardized in RFC 4282, which defines a Network Access Identifier (NAI) in the form of 'user@realm'.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] In that specification, the 'realm' portion is required to be a domain name.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] However, this practice is not always followed.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] When a RADIUS server receives an AAA request for a user name containing a realm, the server will reference a table of configured realms.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] If the realm is known, the server will then *proxy* the request to the configured home server for that domain.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The behavior of the proxying server regarding the removal of the realm from the request ("stripping") is configuration-dependent on most servers.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] In addition, the proxying server can be configured to add, remove or rewrite AAA requests when they are proxied over time again.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Proxy Chaining is possible in RADIUS and authentication/authorization and accounting packets are usually routed between a NAS Device and a Home server through a series of proxies.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Some of advantages of using proxy chains include scalability improvements, policy implementations and capability adjustments.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] But in roaming scenarios, the NAS, Proxies and Home Server could be typically managed by different administrative entities.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Hence, the trust factor among the proxies gains more significance under such Inter-domain applications.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Further, the absence of end to end security in RADIUS adds to the criticality of trust among the Proxies involved.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Roaming with RADIUS exposes the users to various security and privacy concerns.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] More generally, some roaming partners establish a secure tunnel between the RADIUS servers to ensure that users' credentials cannot be intercepted while being proxied across the internet.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] This is a concern as the MD5 hash built into RADIUS is considered insecure.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS is transported over UDP on ports 1812 and 1813..
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RadSec (RADIUS over TLS) uses TCP port 2083 by default.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RADIUS packet data format is shown to the right.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The fields are transmitted from left to right, starting with the code, the identifier, the length, the authenticator and the attributes.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The Identifier field aids in matching requests and replies.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The Length field indicates the length of the entire RADIUS packet including the Code, Identifier, Length, Authenticator and optional Attribute fields.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The Authenticator is used to authenticate the reply from the RADIUS server, and is used in encrypting passwords; its length is 16 bytes.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RADIUS Attribute Value Pairs (AVP) carry data in both the request and the response for the authentication, authorization, and accounting transactions.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The length of the radius packet is used to determine the end of the AVPs.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS is extensible; many vendors of RADIUS hardware and software implement their own variants using Vendor-Specific Attributes (VSAs).
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Microsoft has published some of their VSAs.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] VSA definitions from many other companies remain proprietary and/or ad hoc, nonetheless many VSA dictionaries can be found by downloading the source code of open source RADIUS implementations, for example FreeRADIUS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] For example, some vendors drop the "Vendor Length" field, or they use 2 octets for the "Vendor Type" and/or the "Vendor Length" fields.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RFC 8044 Section 3.14 defines the "vsa" data type which mandates the RFC 2865 Section 5.26 format.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RADIUS protocol transmits obfuscated passwords using a shared secret and the MD5 hashing algorithm.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] As this particular implementation provides only weak protection of the user's credentials, additional protection, such as IPsec tunnels or physically secured data-center networks, should be used to further protect the RADIUS traffic between the NAS device and the RADIUS server.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RadSec protocol addresses the issue with legacy RADIUS/UDP security by "wrapping" the RADIUS protocol in TLS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] However, the packets inside of the TLS transport still use MD5 for packet integrity checks and for obfuscating the contents of certain attributes.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The Blast-RADIUS attack breaks RADIUS when it is transported by plain UDP by attacking MD5 within RADIUS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Another recommended mitigation is to require Message-Authenticator attributes for all requests and responses.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] CVE-2024-3596 has been assigned for the Blast-RADIUS attack.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] As more dial-up customers used the NSFNET a request for proposal was sent out by Merit Network in 1991 to consolidate their various proprietary authentication, authorization and accounting systems.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Among the early respondents was Livingston Enterprises and an early version of the RADIUS was written after a meeting.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The early RADIUS server was installed on a UNIX operating system.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Livingston Enterprises was acquired by Lucent Technologies and together with Merit steps were taken to gain industry acceptance for RADIUS as a protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Both companies offered a RADIUS server at no charge.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] In 1997 RADIUS was published as RFC 2058 and RFC 2059, current versions are RFC 2865 and RFC 2866.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The original RADIUS standard specified that RADIUS is stateless and should run over the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:radius-protocol/radius] For authentication, it was envisaged that RADIUS should support the Password Authentication Protocol (PAP) and the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) over the Point-to-Point Protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Passwords are hidden by taking the MD5 hash of the packet and a shared secret, and then XORing that hash with the password.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The original RADIUS also provided more than 50 attribute-value pairs, with the possibility for vendors to configure their own pairs.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The choice of the hop-by-hop security model, rather than end-to-end encryption, meant that if several proxy RADIUS servers are in use, every server must examine, perform logic on and pass on all data in a request.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] This exposes data such as passwords and certificates at every hop.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS servers also did not have the ability to stop access to resources once an authorisation had been issued.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Subsequent standards such as RFC 3576 and its successor RFC 5176 allowed for RADIUS servers to dynamically change a users authorization, or to disconnect a user entirely.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Now, several commercial and open-source RADIUS servers exist.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Features can vary, but most can look up the users in text files, LDAP servers, various databases, etc.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Accounting records can be written to text files, various databases, forwarded to external servers, etc.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] SNMP is often used for remote monitoring and keep-alive checking of a RADIUS server.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] RADIUS proxy servers are used for centralized administration and can rewrite RADIUS packets on the fly for security reasons, or to convert between vendor dialects.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The Diameter protocol was intended as the replacement for RADIUS.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] While both are Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting (AAA) protocols, the use cases for the two protocols have since diverged.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Diameter is largely used in the 3G space.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] One of the largest barriers to having Diameter replace RADIUS is that switches and access points typically implement RADIUS, but not Diameter.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] Diameter uses SCTP or TCP while RADIUS typically uses UDP as the transport layer.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] As of 2012, RADIUS can also use TCP as the transport layer with TLS for security.
[src:radius-protocol/radius] The RADIUS protocol is currently defined in the following IETF RFC documents.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS was originally developed in 1984 by BBN, later known as BBN Technologies, for administration of ARPANET and MILNET, which ran unclassified network traffic for DARPA at the time and would later evolve into the U.S.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] Cisco Systems began supporting TACACS in its networking products in the late 1980s, eventually adding several extensions to the protocol.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] In 1990, Cisco's extensions on top of TACACS became a proprietary protocol called Extended TACACS (XTACACS).
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] Although TACACS and XTACACS are not open standards, Craig Finseth of the University of Minnesota, with Cisco's assistance, published a description of the protocols in 1993 as IETF RFC 1492 for informational purposes.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS is defined in RFC 1492, and uses (either TCP or UDP) port 49 by default.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS allows a client to accept a username and password and send a query to a TACACS authentication server, sometimes called a TACACS daemon.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] It determines whether to accept or deny the authentication request and sends a response back.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] The TIP (routing node accepting dial-up line connections, which the user would normally want to log in into) would then allow access or not, based upon the response.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] In this way, the process of making the decision is "opened up" and the algorithms and data used to make the decision are under the complete control of whoever is running the TACACS daemon.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] Extended TACACS (XTACACS) extends the TACACS protocol with additional functionality.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] It also separates the authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) functions out into separate processes, allowing them to be handled by separate servers and technologies.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ is a Cisco-designed extension to TACACS that is described in RFC 8907.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ includes a mechanism that can be used to obfuscate the body of each packet, while leaving the header clear-text.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] Moreover, it provides granular control in the form of command-by-command authorization.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ has generally replaced TACACS and XTACACS in more recently built or updated networks.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ is an entirely new protocol which is not compatible with its predecessors, TACACS and XTACACS.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] There are a number of differences between the two protocols which make them substantially different in normal usage.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ can only use TCP, while RADIUS normally operates over UDP, but can also use TCP (RFC6613), and for additional security, TLS (RFC 6614) and DTLS (RFC7360).
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] One mode is where all traffic including passwords are sent in clear-text, and the only security is IP address filtering.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] The other mode is data obfuscation (RFC 8907 Section 4.5), where the packet header is clear-text, but the body including passwords is obfuscated with an MD5-based method.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] The MD5-based obfuscation method is similar to that used for the RADIUS User-Password attribute (RFC 2865 Section 5.2), and therefore has similar security properties.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] Another difference is that TACACS+ is used only for administrator access to networking equipment, while RADIUS is most often used for end-user authentication.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ supports "command authorization", where an administrator can log in to a piece of networking equipment, and attempt to issue commands.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] The equipment will use TACACS+ to send each command to a TACACS+ server, which can choose to authorize, or reject the command.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] Similar functionality exists in RADIUS in RFC 5607, but support for that standard appears to be poor or non-existent.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] TACACS+ offers robust functionality for administrator authentication and command authorization, but is essentially never used for authenticating end-user access to networks.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] In contrast, RADIUS offers minimal functionality for administrator authentication and command authorization, while offering strong support (and is widely used) for end-user authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:radius-protocol/tacacs] As such, the two protocols have little overlap in functionality or in common usage.
